items.name: Raids on Tripoli airport echo power struggle
items.shortDescription: Libya's Tobruk-based government says it carried out attack on rival-held Mitiga airport on Monday.
items.longDescription: Libya's Tobruk-based Prime Minister Abdullah al-Thinni has said his government has carried out air strikes on the airport in Tripoli. The air raids in the capital are the latest round in the deadly power-struggle between the country's two rival administrations. Al Jazeera's Nicole Johnston reports.
items.linkText: Raids on Tripoli airport echo power struggle

items.name: Jerusalem tram stops trace tale of tragedy
items.shortDescription: City's tram system is one of the few places where you can still find both Israelis and Palestinians in the same place.
items.longDescription: Residents across Jerusalem remain on high alert a week after five Israelis were killed in a synagogue by Palestinian attackers, prompting more violence on both sides.The city's tram is now one of the few places where you can find both Israelis and Palestinians in the same place.Stop by stop the route follows a modern timeline of division and tragedy.Al Jazeera's Andrew Simmons reports from occupied East Jerusalem.
items.linkText: Jerusalem tram stops trace tale of tragedy

items.name: Former UK envoy to Iran discusses nuclear talks
items.shortDescription: Richard Dalton, former UK ambassador to Iran, told Al Jazeera that Tehran's negotiations with the West over its nuclear programme had good chances of reaching at least a partial deal.
items.longDescription: Richard Dalton, former UK ambassador to Iran, told Al Jazeera that Tehran's negotiations with the West over its nuclear programme had good chances of reaching at least a partial deal.He says political leaders and negotiators should "keep calm and carry on".

items.name: Security concerns as Tunisians vote for president
items.shortDescription: Human rights groups are concerned at freedoms being sacrificed as it tries to stop more Tunisians from fighting in Syria and Iraq.
items.longDescription: Tunisians are worried about the continuous unjust arrests taking place in their country.  Tunisia's Interior Ministry has turned down requests to speak about alleged human rights violations. But in the past it has said the security threat is real and constant.  Al Jazeera's Nazanine Moshiri reports from Tunis.
items.linkText: Tunisia's Essebsi wins first round of poll

items.shortDescription: UN Human Rights chief speaks to Al Jazeera's James Bays.
items.longDescription: UN High Commissioner for Human Rights, Zeid Ra'ad al Hussein,  reacts to the execution of Peter Kassig.

items.name: Morocco flash floods leave dozens dead
items.shortDescription: At least 31 people washed away and dozens missing as storm hits southern part of the north African country.
items.longDescription: Flash flooding in southern Morocco has reportedly killed at least 31 people, with many others still missing.The "exceptional" storms also swept across the regions of Guelmim, Agadir and Ouarzazate, and a search was under way for the missing, the authorities said.Al Jazeera's Kim Vinnell reports.Subscribe to our channel http://bit.ly/AJSubscribeFollow us on Twitter https://twitter.com/AJEnglishFind us on Facebook https://www.facebook.com/aljazeeraCheck our website http://www.aljazeera.com/

items.name: Iraqi forces reclaim two key towns from ISIL
items.shortDescription: Aided by Shia armed groups and Peshmerga forces, Iraqi troops launch biggest operation against ISIL since June.
items.longDescription: Iraqi forces have mounted their biggest operation since June, reclaiming two towns in the eastern province of Diyala from Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) fighters.  In the province's south on Sunday, Iraqi troops and Shia militias retook the town of Sa'adiya and were moving towards nearby villages.  In the north, Kurdish Peshmerga forces retook the town of Jawlala and were securing the area.   Al Jazeera's Imran Khan reports from Baghdad. items.name: Yemeni tribesmen prepare to face Houthis
items.shortDescription: Shia Houthis rebels and Sunni tribesmen have been gathering fighters in the oil and gas rich province of Maarib.
items.longDescription: A power plant in the Yemeni city of Maarib which supplies power to the capital Sanaa and many of the surrounding provinces, has been shut down after it was attacked by tribesmen.  Shia Houthis rebels and Sunni tribesmen have been gathering fighters in the oil and gas rich province of Maarib - a sign of an increasing sectarian divide in the country.   Al Jazeera's Hashem Ahelbarra reports from Sanaa. items.name: Peshmerga critical of air-strikes strategy
items.shortDescription: Kurdish commanders complain of insufficient support as coalition battling ISIL makes gains but sustain losses too.
items.longDescription: Several months of US-led air strikes have pushed back the Islamic State in Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) in some areas, but the fighters have managed to advance elsewhere.Kurdish Peshmerga forces are critical of the strategy behind the air campaign. Their commanders say they are not getting the support they need, and even accuse the US of having a certain "tolerance" towards ISIL's advance.For his part, Haidar al-Abadi, Iraq's prime minister, has called for more air support. And in a Pentagon document addressed to Congress, the US says it will expand its influence in the battle against ISIL "with, by and through" Iraq's government.Al Jazeera's Imran Khan reports from Baghdad.Subscribe to our channel http://bit.ly/AJSubscribeFollow us on Twitter https://twitter.com/AJEnglishFind us on Facebook https://www.facebook.com/aljazeeraCheck our website http://www.aljazeera.com/

items.name: Tunisians vote in landmark presidential poll
items.shortDescription: Early voter turnout in first presidential election since 2011 revolution is low, especially among the youths.
items.longDescription: Millions of Tunisians are casting their ballots to directly elect their president for the first time since the revolution four years ago that swept away longtime leader Zine El Abidine Ben Ali.  Al Jazeera's Nazanine Moshiri reports from Tunis
items.linkText: Polls close in Tunisia's first free election

items.name: Syrians in Lebanon fearful about future
items.shortDescription: Many among the million-plus refugees wonder whether, with their new lives and jobs, they will be going back some day.
items.longDescription: The war in Syria has forced millions of people to leave their homes, with over a million in neighbouring Lebanon. They tell the stories of their new lives and jobs and explain how the conflict has affected their lives.As Al Jazeera's Zeina Khodr reports from Beirut, many of them wonder whether they will be able to go back home one day.Subscribe to our channel http://bit.ly/AJSubscribeFollow us on Twitter https://twitter.com/AJEnglishFind us on Facebook https://www.facebook.com/aljazeeraCheck our website http://www.aljazeera.com/
items.linkText: Syrians in Lebanon fearful about future

items.name: Tunisia to vote in historic presidential poll
items.shortDescription: Election billed as first free and fair poll since independence pits new generation of politicians against old guard.
items.longDescription: Tunisians are heading to the polls on Sunday for presidential elections.  For the first time since the revolution in 2011, they  will be able to choose a new leader.  The election is being seen as important for the whole region.  Al Jazeera's Omar al Saleh reports from Tunis.
items.linkText: Tunisia votes in historic presidential poll

items.name: Polls close in boycotted Bahrain elections
items.shortDescription: Opposition group boycotts first election and warns of violence but government says it will not tolerate any "chaos".
items.longDescription: In Bahrain, the largest Shia muslim party is boycotting parliamentary elections.It is the first time voters have gone to the polls since a government crackdown on Shia-led protests three-years ago. There have been been demonstrations in the north western village of Diraz, where riot police used tear gas. Al Jazeera's Nicole Johnston reports.

items.name: Bahrain votes amid Shia boycott calls
items.shortDescription: Opposition group vows to boycott first election since a 2011 uprising was crushed by the Gulf nation's Sunni rulers.
items.longDescription: Bahrain is holding its first parliamentary election since a crackdown on protests in 2011. However, the country's Shia opposition says the government has failed to address any of the grievances that sparked those demonstrations in the first place. Al Jazeera's Charles Stratford reports. items.name: Battle rages in a Damascus suburb
items.shortDescription: Heavy fighting has been reported in a suburb of Damascus as government forces loyal to Syrian President Bashar al-Assad try to wrest the area from control of rebel fighters.The suburb of Jobar on Saturday was the scene of some of the heaviest fight
items.longDescription: Heavy fighting has been reported in a suburb of Damascus as government forces loyal to Syrian President Bashar al-Assad try to wrest the area from control of rebel fighters.The suburb of Jobar on Saturday was the scene of some of the heaviest fighting the rebels holding the area have seen in the past year

items.name: Tycoon among Tunisia presidential hopefuls
items.shortDescription: Slim Riahi, who has big stake in nation's media and owns a football team, impresses young students and the unemployed.
items.longDescription: Wealthy businessman Slim Riahi has emerged as a surprise contender in the race for Tunisia's presidency.  The 36-year-old media tycoon, who's been compared with former Italian prime minister Silvio Berlusconi, has seen his support grow with students and the unemployed backing his bid.  Al Jazeera's Nazanine Moshiri reports from Tunis.

items.name: Civilians suffer in battle for Syria's Golan
items.shortDescription: Residents along the Israeli border say despite taking refuge in a 'ceasefire zone' they still face regular bombardment.
items.longDescription: Syrians living inside a buffer zone along the Israeli-occupied Golan Heights are increasingly being caught up in the country's civil war.  UN observers were removed from the Syrian side of the demarcation line in September when rebel fighters advanced.  But civilians say despite taking refuge in the so called 'ceasefire zone', they are still coming under regular bombardment by Syrian government forces.  Al Jazeera's Kim Vinnell reports.
items.linkText: Civilians suffer in battle for Syria's Golan

items.name: Al-Qaeda in Yemen claims 'Houthi killings'
items.shortDescription: Shia fighters declare expansion into north and reject AQAP claim, saying they know of no deadly attack in Radaa.
items.longDescription: Al-Qaeda's branch in Yemen says it has killed 12 Houthi fighters in the central city of Radaa, a claim denied by the Shia group, which continues to move southwards after its takeover of the capital Sanaa in September.  Al Jazeera's Hashem Ahelbarra reports from Sanaa.

items.name: Deadline looms over Iran nuclear deal
items.shortDescription: US Secretary of State arrives in Vienna to try and save talks on Iran's nuclear programme, with just four days left to reach agreement.
items.longDescription: US Secretary of State John Kerry has arrived in Vienna to try and save talks on Iran's nuclear programme.Iran and six world powers are trying to reach a deal before Monday's deadline.  But the most difficult issues have been saved until last - and the talks are beginning to falter.Al Jazeera's James Bays reports from UN headquarters in New York.
